lo-Indians... an exploration through history, identity and photography]\n\n{{British diaspora}}\n{{Kollam |state=collapsed}}\n{{NRI-PIO}}\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Indian people|*]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in India]]\n[[Category:Culture of Kollam]]\n[[Category:Europeans in India]]\n[[Category:Multiracial affairs in Asia]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Immigration to India|Anglo-Indian]]\n[[Category:British India]]\n", "name_user": "Klbrain", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnglo-Indians of mixed South Asian and European descent (modern definition - alphabetic):Fixing broken link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Indian"}
{"title_page": "Aniene", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name              =Aniene\n| image             =Aqua alsietina planlatium.jpg\n| image_caption     =An 1886 [[German language|German]] map of the settlements, [[Roman road|roads]], and [[Roman aqueduct|aqueducts]] around [[ancient Rome]]. The Anio is the principal left-hand tributary of the [[Tiber River|Tiber]], joining it just north of Rome.\n| map               = Aniene.png\n| source1_location  =Filettino\n| mouth_location    =[[Tiber]] ([[Rome]], ponte Salario)\n| mouth_coordinates = {{coord|41.941745|12.50181|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 =[[Italy]]\n| length            ={{convert|99|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| source1_elevation ={{convert|1075|m|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg    =\n| basin_size        ={{convert|1414|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}\n}}\nThe '''Aniene''' ({{IPA-it|a\u02c8nj\u025b\u02d0ne|pron}}; {{lang-la|Anio}}), formerly known as the '''Teverone''',{{sfnp|EB|1878}} is a {{convert|99|km|mi|sp=us|adj=on}} [[river]] in [[Lazio]], [[Italy]]. It originates in the [[Apennines]] at [[Trevi nel Lazio]] and flows westward past [[Subiaco, Italy|Subiaco]], [[Vicovaro]], and [[Tivoli, Italy|Tivoli]] to join the [[Tiber]] in northern [[Rome]]. It thus formed the principal valley east of [[ancient Rome]] and was an important water source as the city's population expanded. The falls at Tivoli were noted for their beauty.{{sfnp|EB|1878}} Historic bridges across the river include the [[Ponte Nomentano]], Ponte Mammolo, [[Ponte Salario]], and [[Ponte di San Francesco]], all of which were originally fortified with towers.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Aqua Anio Novus|Aqua Marcia}}\n{{stack|[[File:Cascade of Aniene - Tivoli - 1890.jpg|thumb|Cascade of the river Aniene in [[Tivoli, Lazio|Tivoli]], 1890.]]}}\nThe confluence of the Aniene and [[Tiber]] was controlled by [[Antemnae]], a [[Latins (Italic tribe)|Latin]] settlement on a hill just to its south. [[Founding of Rome|Rome's foundation myths]] numbered them among the [[Sabines]] [[Rape of the Sabine Women|seized]] by [[Romulus]] but that his wife [[Hersilia]] convinced him to make its people [[Roman citizenship|Roman citizens]] after their defeat and annexation around 752&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.<ref>{{cite book |author=Livy |author-link=Livy |title=From the Founding of the City |volume=[[s:From the Founding of the City/Book 1#11|(I,11)]]}}</ref>\n[[File:Aquae planlatium 2a.png|thumb|300px|Map showing aqueduct sources]]\n[[file:99 04 aniene a subiaco.jpg|thumb|The Aniene in [[Subiaco, Italy|Subiaco]].]]\nIn [[classical antiquity|antiquity]], three principal [[Roman aqueducts|aqueducts]] of [[ancient Rome|Rome]]\u2014the [[Aqua Anio Vetus]], [[Aqua Anio Novus]] and [[Aqua Claudia]]\u2014had their sources in the Aniene valley.  Together with the [[Aqua Marcia]], they were regarded as the \"four great aqueducts of Rome.\"<ref>Blackman, Deane R. \"The Volume of Water Delivered by the Four Great Aqueducts of Rome.\" Papers of the British School at Rome 46 (1978): 52-72. https://www.jstor.org/stable/40310747.</ref> The Aqua Anio Vetus ([[Latin]] for \"Old Anio aqueduct\") was constructed around 270&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.{{sfnp|EB|1878}} The Aqua Anio Novus (\"New Anio aqueduct\") was begun under [[Caligula]] around {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;38 and completed under [[Claudius]] in 48.{{sfnp|EB|1878}} A third aqueduct, the Aqua Marcia, was constructed by [[Quintus Marcius Rex (praetor 144 BC)|Q. Marcius Rex]] between 144 and 140&nbsp;{{sc|bc}} using the proceeds from the destructions of [[Battle of Corinth (146 BC)|Corinth]] and [[Third Punic War|Carthage]] in 146&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.\n\nThe emperor [[Nero]] created three lakes on the river for his villa at [[Subiaco, Italy|Subiaco]]. The [[Subiaco Dam|largest of these dams]] was the [[List of Roman dams and reservoirs|highest dam in classical antiquity]] and remained in use until its destruction by a flood in 1305.{{sfnp|Smith|1970|pp=60\u201361}}{{sfnp|Smith|1971|p=26}}{{sfnp|Schnitter|1978|p=28}}{{sfnp|Hodge|1992|p=87}} [[Trajan]] eventually connected the Anio Novus to two of these lakes.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nThe former site of Antemnae is now the ruins of Forte Monte Antenne, which was erected by the [[Kingdom of Italy]] between 1877 and 1891.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Roman aqueduct#Rome.27s Aqueducts|Rome's Aqueducts]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{citation |contribution=[[s:Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Ninth Edition/Anio|Anio]] |title=''[[s:Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Ninth Edition|''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', 9th ed.]], [[s:Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Ninth Edition/Volume II|Vol.&nbsp;II]]'' |editor-last=Baynes |editor-first=Thomas Spencer |display-editors=0 |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |location=New York |date=1878 |ref={{harvid|EB|1878}} |p=57 }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last = Hodge\n | first = A. Trevor\n | title = Roman Aqueducts & Water Supply\n | place = London\n | publisher = Duckworth\n | year = 1992\n | isbn = 0-7156-2194-7\n}}\n*{{Citation\n | last = Schnitter\n | first = Niklaus\n | title = R\u00f6mische Talsperren\n | journal = Antike Welt\n | volume = 8\n | issue = 2\n | pages = 25\u201332\n | year = 1978\n}}\n*{{Citation\n | last = Smith\n | first = Norman \n | title = The Roman Dams of Subiaco\n | journal = Technology and Culture\n | volume = 11\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 58\u201368\n | year = 1970\n | doi=10.2307/3102810\n}}\n*{{Citation\n | last = Smith\n | first = Norman\n | title = A History of Dams\n | place = London\n | publisher = Peter Davies\n | year = 1971\n | isbn = 0-432-15090-0\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{commons category-inline|Aniene}}\n*[http://www.simbruinastagna.com/ Simbruina Stagna History and Art of Subiaco] (Italian site)\n\n[[Category:Geography of Rome]]\n[[Category:Rivers of the Province of Rome]]\n[[Category:Rivers of the Province of Frosinone]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Italy]]\n\n\n{{Lazio-geo-stub}}\n{{Italy-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name              =Aniene\n| image             =Aqua alsietina planlatium.jpg\n| image_caption     =An 1886 [[German language|German]] map of the settlements, [[Roman road|roads]], and [[Roman aqueduct|aqueducts]] around [[ancient Rome]]. The Anio is the principal left-hand tributary of the [[Tiber River|Tiber]], joining it just north of Rome.\n| map               = Aniene.png\n| source1_location  =Filettino\n| mouth_location    =[[Tiber]] ([[Rome]], ponte Salario)\n| mouth_coordinates = {{coord|41.941745|12.50181|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 =[[Italy]]\n| length            ={{convert|99|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| source1_elevation ={{convert|1075|m|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg    =\n| basin_size        ={{convert|1414|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}\n}}\nThe '''Aniene''' ({{IPA-it|a\u02c8nj\u025b\u02d0ne|pron}}; {{lang-la|Anio}}), formerly known as the '''Teverone''',{{sfnp|EB|1878}} is a {{convert|99|km|mi|sp=us|adj=on}} [[river]] in [[Lazio]], [[Italy]]. It originates in the [[Apennines]] at [[Trevi nel Lazio]] and flows westward past [[Subiaco, Italy|Subiaco]], [[Vicovaro]], and [[Tivoli, Italy|Tivoli]] to join the [[Tiber]] in northern [[Rome]]. It thus formed the principal valley east of [[ancient Rome]] and was an important water source as the city's population expanded. The falls at Tivoli were noted for their beauty.{{sfnp|EB|1878}} Historic bridges across the river include the [[Ponte Nomentano]], Ponte Mammolo, [[Ponte Salario]], and [[Ponte di San Francesco]], all of which were originally fortified with towers.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Aqua Anio Novus|Aqua Marcia}}\n{{stack|[[File:Cascade of Aniene - Tivoli - 1890.jpg|thumb|Cascade of the river Aniene in [[Tivoli, Lazio|Tivoli]], 1890.]]}}\nThe confluence of the Aniene and [[Tiber]] was controlled by [[Antemnae]], a [[Latins (Italic tribe)|Latin]] settlement on a hill just to its south. [[Founding of Rome|Rome's foundation myths]] numbered them among the [[Sabines]] [[Rape of the Sabine Women|seized]] by [[Romulus]] but that his wife [[Hersilia]] convinced him to make its people [[Roman citizenship|Roman citizens]] after their defeat and annexation around 752&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.<ref>{{cite book |author=Livy |author-link=Livy |title=From the Founding of the City |volume=[[s:From the Founding of the City/Book 1#11|(I,11)]]}}</ref>\n[[File:Aquae planlatium 2a.png|thumb|300px|Map showing aqueduct sources]]\n[[file:99 04 aniene a subiaco.jpg|thumb|The Aniene in [[Subiaco, Italy|Subiaco]].]]\nIn [[classical antiquity|antiquity]], three principal [[Roman aqueducts|aqueducts]] of [[ancient Rome|Rome]]\u2014the [[Aqua Anio Vetus]], [[Aqua Anio Novus]] and [[Aqua Claudia]]\u2014had their sources in the Aniene valley.  Together with the [[Aqua Marcia]], they were regarded as the \"four great aqueducts of Rome.\"<ref>Blackman, Deane R. \"The Volume of Water Delivered by the Four Great Aqueducts of Rome.\" Papers of the British School at Rome 46 (1978): 52-72. https://www.jstor.org/stable/40310747.</ref> The Aqua Anio Vetus ([[Latin]] for \"Old Anio aqueduct\") was constructed around 270&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.{{sfnp|EB|1878}} The Aqua Anio Novus (\"New Anio aqueduct\") was begun under [[Caligula]] around {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;38 and completed under [[Claudius]] in 48.{{sfnp|EB|1878}} A third aqueduct, the Aqua Marcia, was constructed by [[Quintus Marcius Rex (praetor 144 BC)|Q. Marcius Rex]] between 144 and 140&nbsp;{{sc|bc}} using the proceeds from the destructions of [[Battle of Corinth (146 BC)|Corinth]] and [[Third Punic War|Carthage]] in 146&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.\n\nThe emperor [[Nero]] created three lakes on the river for his villa at [[Subiaco, Italy|Subiaco]]. The [[Subiaco Dam|largest of these dams]] was the [[List of Roman dams and reservoirs|highest dam in classical antiquity]] and remained in use until its destruction by a flood in 1305.{{sfnp|Smith|1970|pp=60\u201361}}{{sfnp|Smith|1971|p=26}}{{sfnp|Schnitter|